      "content": "My apologies; I sometimes get carried away with the finer points of textile engineering, which I assure you is a delicate operation, much like trying to coax a reluctant, grumpy little hobbit out of his burrow. Regarding structural integrity, the interlocking in a high-density percale relies on the *crimp* and the *friction* between the fine, tightly spun yarns.\n\nWhen the yarns are extremely fine (low denier), they have a higher surface area relative to their mass, which maximizes the points of contact where the warp and weft cross over and under each other. This dense crossing creates immense frictional resistance. If the yarns are too thick, the individual threads can slide past each other under tension because the contact points are fewer and the yarn structure itself is too rigid to conform to the weave pattern.\n\nIn a high-density percale, the weave structure itself is simple—over one, under one—but the *precision* of the yarn ensures that this simple geometry locks down perfectly. It's the microscopic grip, not just the pattern, that prevents slippage. You are essentially creating a mesh so fine that the yarns are physically trapped against each other.\n\nThis is analogous to how a swarm of highly organized, tiny",
